{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626469"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:38:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:38:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17076"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17076"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.08,0.14,0.56,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9766"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69297"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9766"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17076"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54750"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"108"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"5263"},{"type":"tags","id":"10851"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22944"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23191"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69297"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ERifampicin is an antibiotic utilised in the treatment of tuberculosis and other mycobacterial infections.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of rifampicin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Interferes with bacterial DNA gyrase","Blocks bacterial protein synthesis","Inhibits bacterial cell wall synthesis","Binds to bacterial RNA polymerase beta subunit","Disrupts bacterial cell membrane integrity"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinding to bacterial RNA polymerase beta subunit\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of action of rifampicin. This mechanism prevents transcription initiation, thereby inhibiting bacterial RNA synthesis thus causing cell death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterference with bacterial DNA gyrase\u003C/strong\u003E represents the mechanism of action of fluoroquinolone antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking bacterial protein synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E describes how aminoglycosides and tetracyclines exert their antimicrobial effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of bacterial cell wall synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of beta-lactam antibiotics and vancomycin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisruption of bacterial cell membrane integrity\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of action of polymyxins and daptomycin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERifampicin\u0027s mechanism makes it effective against slow-growing organisms like \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E. It is also a potent inducer of cytochrome P450 enzymes, which can lead to significant drug interactions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rifampicin inhibits bacterial RNA polymerase by binding to its beta subunit, preventing transcription initiation.","Rifampicin is bactericidal and particularly effective against mycobacteria due to their slow growth rate.","Rifampicin is a potent inducer of cytochrome P450 enzymes, leading to significant drug interactions."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54750"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17076"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54750"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T18:30:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T18:31:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9766"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69297"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","posi